1
00:00:00,000 --> 00:00:10,640
Crawl back with you for Chapter 2. Every commercial and legal transaction carries a unique risk profile requiring highly targeted bond instruments.

2
00:00:10,640 --> 00:00:18,040
The industry categorizes these into two primary divisions: fidelity bonds and surety bonds.

3
00:00:18,040 --> 00:00:27,280
Fidelity bonds strictly guarantee the personal honesty of individuals, usually employees handling corporate funds like cashiers or collectors.

4
00:00:27,280 --> 00:00:33,560
Do not confuse a traditional three-party fidelity bond with a two-party fidelity guarantee.

5
00:00:33,560 --> 00:00:41,320
A true fidelity bond requires a prior conviction clause to be present before a claim responds.

6
00:00:41,320 --> 00:00:50,360
These can be issued as individual bonds or as blanket types structured as name schedule or position schedule bonds.

7
00:00:50,360 --> 00:01:00,160
All other obligations fall under the broader category of surety bonds, which are split into judicial and non-judicial lines.

8
00:01:00,160 --> 00:01:12,080
Judicial bonds are required by courts during legal proceedings. In criminal matters, an accused individual posts a bail bond to secure temporary liberty.

9
00:01:12,080 --> 00:01:26,000
In civil litigation, a replevin bond is posted to repossess personal property, while a supersedeas bond is mandatory in labor cases to stay the execution of a judgment pending an appeal.

10
00:01:26,000 --> 00:01:35,160
If a minor is designated to receive insurance proceeds, a guardian's bond is legally required to protect those assets.

11
00:01:35,160 --> 00:01:45,040
On the non-judicial side, you will most frequently handle contractor's bonds, which manage risk sequentially through every phase of a project life cycle.

12
00:01:45,040 --> 00:01:51,800
The bidding phase: A bidder's bond ensures the participant has bona fide intentions.

13
00:01:51,800 --> 00:02:04,280
If the winning contractor refuses to sign the contract, this bond answers for the cost to conduct a new bidding and covers the financial gap between the winning bid and the next lowest bidder.

14
00:02:04,280 --> 00:02:14,560
The awarding phase: A performance bond, typically valued at 10% to 30% of the total contract price, guarantees completion according to specifications.

15
00:02:14,560 --> 00:02:29,240
It covers the costs of delays and the financial premium of hiring a replacement contractor. Simultaneously, a down payment bond guarantees the exact liquidation of any advance payments given to the contractor.

16
00:02:29,240 --> 00:02:37,840
The completion phase: Prior to final acceptance, a warranty or guarantee bond is deployed.

17
00:02:37,840 --> 00:02:50,120
It allows the obligee to safely release retention money because it guarantees that the contractor must repair any hidden defects in materials or workmanship that appear within 1 year.

18
00:02:50,120 --> 00:02:59,840
Understanding the product is only half the battle. Next, we must analyze the strict underwriting standards required to manage these exposures safely.